- For the test that needs to be added, I think I should explain, because the unit of `AutoIntervalShardingAlgorithm` is only `seconds`, it does not allow to modify this unit. And there is a step in the function `Duration.between(dateTimeLower, dateValueFirst).toMillis() / 1000;` , this will automatically erase all time precision after the second. I've provided my test within this `pull request`, proving that this step will cause something like `2021-10-11 00:00:00.123` Time maps to `2021-10-11 00:00:00`.
````java
 public static void main(String[] args) {
        DateTimeFormatter DATE_TIME_FORMAT = new DateTimeFormatterBuilder()
                .appendPattern("yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss")
                .appendFraction(ChronoField.MILLI_OF_SECOND,0,3,true)
                .toFormatter();
        LocalDateTime dateTimeLower = LocalDateTime.parse("2020-01-01 00:00:00", DATE_TIME_FORMAT);
        LocalDateTime dateValueFirst = LocalDateTime.parse("2021-10-11 00:00:00", DATE_TIME_FORMAT);
        LocalDateTime dateValueSecond = LocalDateTime.parse("2021-10-11 00:00:00.123", DATE_TIME_FORMAT);
        long shardingValueFirst = Duration.between(dateTimeLower, dateValueFirst).toMillis() / 1000;
        System.out.println("shardingValueFirst-->"+shardingValueFirst);
        long shardingValueSecond = Duration.between(dateTimeLower, dateValueFirst).toMillis() / 1000;
        System.out.println("shardingValueSecond-->"+shardingValueSecond);
    }
````
